Contributions to Understanding COVID-19 in the UK







This predictive analytics piece aims to make a small contribution to the understanding of the pandemic using some of the available data on NHS digital. The aim is to shed some descriptive light on the nature of the communities struggling the most with COVID-19. The hope at the time of the development of this body of code was that these predictive analytics, or this way of using the data, would help local authorities by giving them more tools to tackle the pandemic.

The first part of the project is an attempt at characterising the communities which have struggled the most with COVID-19 in the United Kingdom. The second part is the beta version of a notification system which local authorities can action to contact businesses located geographically within these communities and alert them of surges or decreases of COVID-19 cases in the local area as well as provide community-specific information which could help the community tackle specific challenges faced as a result of the pandemic. For example, a community where suspected cases of COVID-19 surged would benefit from local shops offering to deliver food locally. A different community with many elderly members living alone would perhaps benefit from buddy schemes or safe, open-air activities to tackle loneliness and isolation. Other communities where cases would have been observed to decrease perhaps would have appreciated open-air prayers whilst others would prefer organised, safe, open-air activities for families.

The full body of code and instructions to run it can be found on https://github.com/chewingumex/covid-19_predictive_analytics

First Part

Characterising and better understanding the communities struggling with COVID-19 is the first step to design community-specific interventions which can help its members face the difficulties of the pandemic. Fighting isolation, accessing food or basic supplies, avoiding gathering with others whilst combating alienation, promoting adoption of health, wellness and self-care habits are some of the topics which, if tailored to specific communities, are likely to make a much stronger, positive impact. An understanding of the community and a direct line of communication between the authorities and the community is critical to this end.

The clinical data that was used for this project is the publicly available data from NHS digital https://digital.nhs.uk/ In the data summary, the NHS cautions:

      This data is based on potential COVID-19 symptoms reported by members of the public to NHS Pathways through NHS 111 or 999 and 111
      online, and is not based on the outcomes of tests for coronavirus. This is not a count of people. In 111 online, any user that starts
      and launches the COVID-19 assessment services is indicating they may have symptoms of coronavirus. They may have accessed the service
      multiple times with different symptoms.
      At the start of the pandemic, work was undertaken at pace to create a COVID-specific pathway. This was intended to capture all
      patients with symptoms of fever or cough (as defined by Public Health England at that time) and reflected the high prevalence of
      coronavirus in the community.
      Through the pandemic, as further clinical evidence has emerged and the prevalence of coronavirus has decreased, it has become possible
      to more fully integrate this COVID-specific approach with the main NHS Pathways system to ensure that the potential diagnosis of
      COVID-19 is more accurate.
      The initial approach may have overestimated the number of potential coronavirus patients because the symptoms of coronavirus overlap
      with those of other infections not caused by coronavirus, such as colds and flu.

Data from the Organisation of National Statistics (ONS) was extracted and matched to the clinical data from the NHS using the CCG (Clinical Commissioning Group) code of the area. This information provides a social, economical and cultural characterisation of local areas as well as local communities. Below a snippet of the ONS data:

code supergroup group subgroup
6B2 Suburbanites Semi-detached suburbia White suburban communities
4A2 Multicultural metropolitans Rented family living Private renting new arrivals
5B2 Urbanites Ageing urban living Communal retirement
8C1 Hard-pressed living Hard pressed ageing workers Ageing industrious workers
7A2 Constrained city dwellers Challenged diversity Hampered aspiration
1C3 Rural residents Ageing rural dwellers Detached rural retirement

Both data sets were joined by the CCG codes. The data was then pre-processed for modeling. Most of the variables are categorical therefore they were one-hot encoded. All ONS variables were used as predictors of COVID-19 triagecount.

Boosted trees models were fit using the Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBOOST) API. Given the dependent variable is a count of cases in a given extent of time, the objective selected was Poisson, with its corresponding negative log likelihood loss function. The hyper-parameters of each model were tuned in a random search. In the random search, a 5-fold cross validation was performed to get a better estimation of performance with each set of hyper-parameters. The lowest nloglik on the validation set was taken as the metric for the optimal hyper parameters, although of course hyper-parameters could be tuned further.

After fitting each model, variable importance is extracted and plotted. That is the most valuable information for the purposes of characterising the main attributes of the communities and areas struggling with COVID-19 the most. Different models were fit for different attributes of the communities: demographic (i.e. age and gender), socio-economic and cultural attributes, locality-related attributes and CCG names.

Any granularity or specificity can be set by filtering the data according to the reports needed (i.e. fitting models on certain dates ranges or CCG subsets). Below the information derived from predictive modeling at a national level:

From the locality analysis, for example, we conclude that major cities have been definitely hit worse than rural towns or small places. Pakistani communities seem also to have been hit the hardest when compared to other social, cultural and ethnic communities. Adults (i.e. not children) and women seem to have been hit the hardest nationally, since the pandemic began. This kind of report could be made more granular (i.e. filtering for date and regions) and local authorities could gain some indication as to which community needs the most support, what kind of strategy ought to be most effective to tackle the pandemic, which social institutions to partner with to reach families, and so on.

Second Part

As explained, the information gained from the above analysis can be used to plan strategy at the level of the community. Plans, instructions, special messaging can be fed back to local communities. Predictive modeling can be done, for example, for the latest month and then recent information about the kinds of communities struggling the most with COVID-19 can be inferred.

Local authorities need a way to inform their communities about the local situation as well as notify them of any precautionary action needed to be taken. Equally, they need to inform the community if there’s a need, for example, for food or basic supplies to be delivered to many people in the area who may be doing self-isolation.

Using publicly available data from the Google Places API, local businesses of each area can be notified of surges or decreases of COVID-19 cases in the local area or any other message which the local council or NHS trust wished to publish quickly. This provides a different information channel other than media companies which can often misrepresent or stir information in one way or another.

Querying a radio of 1.5 miles around the geographical center of the CCG area, a notification address book was built:

Birdcage 80 Columbia Rd, London E2 7QB, UK bar , point_of_interest, establishment E38000186

Then two data sets are made with two cut-off dates to compare them against each other. Two linear models are then fit on these two subsets of data. The coefficients for the CCGs get compared to assess whether the trend of triagecount has gone up or down for the established period and whether that means a surge or decrease of cases in the local area. The variable importance charts below show the valence and magnitude of triagecount per CCG before and after the cutoff dates.

With the advent of mass vaccination it seems that the worst of the pandemic is over and this system may no longer be required for the purposes intended originally. However, this system may be implemented to tackle other issues, implement other social programs or simply strengthen the links between local authorities and communities. Establishing safe channels of information and harnessing the power of communities coming together is the basis of this proposal and it certainly should not be limited to tackling COVID-19.
